operations, it went public, and Koerl moved on. As he was on his way out, h=
e was contacted by a couple of software engineers in Norway. They=E2=80=99d=
 devised an algorithm to scrape the odds off the rudimentary websites of va=
rious bookmakers, and they thought they could make a bundle by laying bets =
that arbitraged the differences. Was Koerl interested in financially backin=
g the idea=3F=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then =
=E2=80=9Cpaying for direct data feeds from monopoly providers=E2=80=9D:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sports, it became possible=
 to purchase data from the associations or the leagues themselves. Tennis l=
ed the way, offering a feed that came right from the chair umpire=E2=80=99s=
 own system. In pro hockey, the least popular of North America=E2=80=99s tr=
aditional Big Four sports, bidding for the NHL=E2=80=99s 10-year betting da=
ta rights reportedly passed $250 million in 2021. Sportradar won that aucti=
on, gaining exclusive access to metrics such as skating speed and shot velo=
city, measured by sensors in pucks and on player jerseys. In 2022, Sportrad=
ar agreed to pay the NBA $1 billion in cash and equity for eight years=E2=
=80=99 worth of data.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And endi=
ng up with =E2=80=9Ceveryone complaining about the high-frequency trading a=
rms race=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The payments=
 for official data have climbed so far that Simon Trim, an adviser to the s=
ports data firm 10star, wonders if they=E2=80=99ve almost ruinously flatten=
ed the market. Trim holds that bookmakers=E2=80=99 odds have become too sim=
ilar, because everyone draws either their odds or the underlying data from =
the same large sources. The big companies, Trim says, have an incentive to =
align the odds they supply with everyone else=E2=80=99s, so as to erase eve=
n the slightest risk of bettors arbitraging variations in prices. =E2=80=9C=
Ten or 15 years ago, there wasn=E2=80=99t this high cost of official data r=
ights,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CThere wasn=E2=80=99t the cost of technolo=
gy.=E2=80=9D As various bookmakers=E2=80=99 odds have converged, margins ha=
ve declined, and sportsbooks have had to differentiate themselves mainly wi=
th =E2=80=9Cdestructive levels of marketing spend to draw new customers,=E2=
=80=9D Trim says. =E2=80=9CIf I=E2=80=99m being honest, a lot of sportsbook=
s are suffering, because their business model doesn=E2=80=99t work anymore.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I love that casual s=
ports fans care about who wins the game, and casual stock market investors =
